These numbers reflect a significant impact of Umrah on further spread of the disease across multiple regions in the world. As of May 23, 2020 (end date of Ramadan), a total of 5,323,000 new COVID-19 cases were reported by WHO (World Health Organization 2020a) which may have been increased by about four million new cases related to pilgrims performing Umrah in Ramadan, where 13% (more than 450,000 cases) of them represents new cases of international pilgrims. Assuming that international flights are not suspended, the estimated numbers of new cases could have lead to a massive increase in the reported cases during the subsequent couple of weeks of Ramadan.Fig. 7
